‘While Jove is sovereign of the sky and Augustus rules on earth, can it he that Crassus' disgraceful defeat is yet unavenged! Has a Roman soldier so forgotten his hirthright as to live under a Median King, married to a barbarian wife! lt was this very thing that Regu· lus' wise mind foresaw when he opposed the ransoming of our soldiers captured by the CarthaginianS‚ a precedent fraught with ill for later times· (1-18). . . . “No,” he said, ‘⁴ let those who yielded die; will they be braver when bought back? No, let thern stay, for they have brought disgrace upon their native ltaly (19-40).” So like one disgraced he put aside his wile and child, and stood with downcast eyes, until the Senate had agreed to his proposal; then he hurried back to torture and to death with heart as light as for a hollday (41—56).'
